  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Solving by Completing the Square">
    <title>Solving by Completing the Square</title>

    <p> If we can't factor our quadratic nicely, the nest thing we can try is to find or create an expression of the form <m>(x+ h)^{2}</m>, then <fillin/> the squared term on a side by itself, and then take the <fillin/> of both sides of the equation. </p>
    
    <p> If the equation does not factor and does not contain an expression of the form $(x+ h)^{2}$? We can use a technique called <term> completing the square</term> to create an expression of the form <m> (x+ h)^{2}</m>. </p>
    
    <p> Before we discuss the technique, we can see a pattern when we expand expressions of the form <m> (x+ h)^{2}</m>. </p>
    
    <p> Use the box method to expand <m>(x-6)^{2}</m>. Notice that in this case, our rectangle in fact becomes a <fillin/> because the sides have <fillin/> length. Fill in the boxes. </p>
