  <subsection xml:id="subsec-The Quadratic Formula">
    <title>The Quadratic Formula</title>
    <p> A third technique to finding the solutions to quadratic equations we call <term> the quadratic formula</term>. The quadratic formula is a result of doing the completing the square process on a generic quadratic equation. (We will not do this in class as it is time consuming. We would be happy to go through it in office hours.) </p>
    
    <definition xml:id="def-quadratic-formula">
      <statement>
        <p> Consider a quadratic equation <m> ax^2+bx+c=0</m>, where <m>a\neq 0</m>. Then the equation has two possible solutions: </p>
        <me>  x=\frac{-b+\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}, x=\frac{-b-\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}  </me>
        <p> These are commonly written as a single equation: </p>
        <me> x=\frac{-b\pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a} . </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p> This formula will work for Real and Complex solutions, but is not elegant to use. It is one of the techniques you will be expected to know coming out of this class, so here are a few problems to practice on. </p>

    <activity>
      <p>  Use the quadratic formula to find the solutions to the following equations.  </p>
      <ol>
        <li>  <p>  <m> 3x^2+x-10=0 </m>  </p> </li>
        <li> <p>  <m> x^2+3x=8 </m> (There is something different about this one.) </p> </li>
        <li>  <p>  <m> x^2+10x-56=0 </m> (Hint: <m>\sqrt{324}=18</m>) </p>  </li>
      </ol>
    </activity>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Complex Numbers">
    <title>Complex Numbers</title>
    <question>
      <p> Consider <m> x^2+1=0</m>. Does it have a solution or solutions? If so, what is unusual about the solutions? </p>
    </question>

    <definition xml:id="def-">
      <statement>
        <p>  We define a special number, <m>i=\sqrt{-1}</m>. We call the number <m>i</m> <term>the Imaginary unit</term>.   </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p> This means that <m>i^2=-1</m>, which allows us to find solutions to problems where squares are negative. (Imaginary unit is a terrible name, since these numbers exist, but we are stuck with it.)</p>
    <p> If <m>x=3i</m>, then what is <m>x^2=</m><fillin/> </p>
    <p> If <m>x=-5i</m>, then what is <m>x^2=</m><fillin/></p>
    <p> If <m>x^2=-16</m>, then what are the two possible (imaginary) values of <m>x</m>?  <m>x=</m><fillin/> and <m>x=</m><fillin/>. </p>
    <p> How about <m>x^2=-7</m>?  <m>x=</m><fillin/> and <m>x=</m><fillin/>. </p>
    <p> Just like <m>(-1)^n</m> alternates between positive and negative values, <m>i</m> also has an interesting pattern for integer powers. We know <m>i^1=\sqrt{-1}</m> is an ``Imaginary'' number, and <m>i^2=-1</m> is a Real number. We can see that powers of <m>i</m> will alternate between imaginary and real. </p>
