    <p> Notice, Integer powers of <m>i</m> only take four values, <m>1,\, i,\,-1,</m> and <m>-i</m>. Thus, powers of <m>i</m> could be either Imaginary or Real. </p>
    <p> We call numbers that can have both Real and Imaginary parts <term>complex numbers</term>. We call the coefficient that multiplies the <m>i</m> the ``Imaginary part'' of the complex number, and the part without the <m>i</m> the ``Real part.'' </p>
