    <activity>
      <p>  Try finding the two solutions to the following equations.  </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p> <m> (x+3)^2=-16.  </m> </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p> <m> x^2-10x = -29.  </m> </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </activity>

    <p> If you look carefully about each pair of complex solutions you notice that the Real parts are <fillin/>, while the Imaginary parts have the same <fillin/> but opposite <fillin/>. </p>
    <p> We call a pair of complex numbers that have the same Real part and the Imaginary part only has a different sign <term>complex conjugates</term>. A quadratic equation with real coefficients that has complex solutions always have a pair of complex conjugate solutions. </p>

